0950 ET - Brazilian crop agency Conab reduces its outlook for the Brazilian sugarcane harvest in the 2024/25 marketing year, now estimating that Brazil will produce 685.86 million tons of sugarcane. While that's a reduction of 3.8% from last year, it would still remain as one of the largest harvests ever recorded. Conab says that the cut was made due to lower rainfall and higher temperatures recorded in the Center-South region of Brazil. Even so, a record amount of 46.29 million tons of sugar are expected to be produced from the sugarcane. Sugar futures on the ICE are off 3.8% today, bringing them down to 19 cents a pound--continuing an easing in sugar prices after they hit a multi-year record of 28 cents a pound in November. title: International Sugar Organization Prices - Apr 16

text:
By Joe Hoppe

A roundup of key agricultural commodity markets for the week April 22-26 by Dow Jones Newswires in Barcelona.

GRAINS & OILSEEDS:

The macro mood is mixed on dollar strength, a headwind for agriculture futures, while falling oil prices have helped to buoy sentiment.

The U.S. dollar's rise has weakened crucial commodity currencies like the Australian and Canadian dollars, as well as the Chinese yuan. Meanwhile, crude strength has a strong correlation with agricultural markets, particularly grains, as it is used throughout the agricultural process from fuel to fertilizer.

South American weather has been wet, delaying Brazil's late soybean harvest and Argentina's early corn and soybean harvest, but forecasts are drier looking forward.

U.S. weather has been cold and rainy heading into the crucial spring planting weeks. Forecasts show some storms will roll through the driest parts of Iowa and Kansas, while the Delta states have been particularly wet. While it is early in the spring planting season, traders are building a risk premium and price seasonals will be bullish until the June summer seasonal high, Peak Trading analysts said in a note.

Several key U.S. macroeconomic data points are coming up, which could change the trajectory of the U.S. dollar, with GDP data on Wednesday and personal consumer expenditure inflation data on Friday. Recent readings show progress curbing inflation has stalled, denting hopes for early interest rate cuts and strengthening the dollar.

There are mixed signals in terms of demand. Brazil's soybean and Argentina's corn demand have been firming due to slow farmer selling and leafhopper disease, but China's import pace has stalled and the country has almost no business booked from the U.S., a bearish signal for U.S. futures, Peak Trading said.

Friday's commitment of traders report indicated hedge funds sold corn, wheat, soybeans, bean oil, cotton, and sugar on soft demand, a hawkish Fed, a strong dollar and weak Brazilian real.

Chicago wheat futures are up 4.5% at $5.92 a bushel, while corn is up 1.2% at $4.48 a bushel. Soybean prices rise 0.65% up at $11.715 a bushel.

SOFT COMMODITIES:

Cocoa prices remain close to all-time highs. The crop's price has nearly tripled since the start of the year and risen 8.2% in the past week alone. The monthslong surge has been driven by supply-side challenges in West Africa, where 70% of global cocoa is produced.

Other soft commodities are also rising. Coffee prices in particular have outperformed the wider complex as unfavorable weather conditions in Brazil and Vietnam continue to fuel bullish sentiment, said BMI, a unit of Fitch Solutions in a note.

ICE-certified coffee arabica stocks increased by 6% between the end of March and April 17, which could dent momentum if sustained, but medium-term precipitation forecasts point to average-at-best rainfall in Vietnam and Brazilian state Minas Gerais between April and June this year, BMI analysts said in a note.

Cocoa is down 0.2% at $11,435 a metric ton, while sugar is up 0.7% at 19.6 cents a pound. Coffee falls 1.8% at $2.28 a pound.

Despite the focus on Primark's margin beat, the strength of grocery, ingredients and sugar businesses was equally impressive, they say in a note.
